Causal functions

As we have seen above, the Laplace transform involves an integral with limits \(t=0\) and \(t=\infty\). Because of this, the nature of the function being transformed, \(f(t)\), when \(t\) is negative is of no importance. In order to emphasize this we shall only consider so-called causal functions all of which take the value \(0\) when \(t<0.\)

The simplest causal function is the Heaviside or unit step function denoted by \(u(t)\) and defined by:

\(\qquad u(t)= \begin{cases} 1& \text{if}\quad t\ge 0\\ 0& \text{if}\quad t<0 \end{cases}\)

with graph as in the following figure.

Similarly we can consider other 'step-functions'. For example, from the above definition we deduce

\( u(t-3)= \begin{cases} 1& \text{if}\quad t-3\ge 0\\ 0& \text{if}\quad t-3<0 \end{cases}\)

or rearranging the inequalities:

\( u(t-3) = \begin{cases} 1& \text{if}\quad t\ge 3\\ 0& \text{if}\quad t<3 \end{cases}\)

with graph as in the following Figure:

The step function has a useful property: multiplying an ordinary function \(f(t)\) by the step function \(u(t)\) changes it into a causal function; e.g. if \(f(t)=\sin t\) then \( \sin t.u(t)\) is causal. This is illustrated in the change bellow:


Key Point

Causal Functions

If \(u(t)\) is the unit step function and \(f(t)\) is any function then

\(f(t)u(t)\) is a causal function

The step function can be used to 'switch on' functions at other values of \(t\) (which we will normally interpret as time). For example \(u(t-1)\) has the value 1 if \(t\ge 1\) and \(0\) otherwise so that \(\sin t.u(t-1)\) is described by the (solid) curve in the following figure:

The step function can also be used to 'switch-off' signals. For example, the step function \(u(t-1)-u(t-3)\) in Figure 7 has the effect on \(f(t)\) such that \(f(t)\left[u(t-1)-u(t-3)\right]\) (described by the solid curve in Figure 8) switches on at \(t=1\) (because then \(u(t-1)-u(t-3)\) takes the value 1), remains 'on' for \(1\le t\le 3\), and then switches 'off' when \(t>3\) (because then \(u(t-1)-u(t-3)=1-1=0\)).


If we have an expression \(f(t − a)u(t − a)\) then this is the function \(f(t)\) translated along the \(t\)-axis through a time a. For example \(\sin(t − 2).u(t − 2)\) is simply the causal sine curve \(\sin t.u(t)\) shifted to the right by two units as described in the following Figure.

Example

Sketch the curve \(f(t)=e^t (u(t-1)-u(t-2)).\)

Solution

You should obtain

This is botained since, if \(t < 1\) then \(t − 1 < 0\) and \(t − 2 < 0\) and so

\( \quad u(t − 1) = 0, \quad u(t − 2) = 0 \quad \) leading to \(f(t) = 0.\)

Also if \(1 < t < 2\) then \(t − 1 > 0\) and \(t − 2 < 0\) so

\( \quad u(t − 1) = 1 \quad \) and \(\quad u(t − 2) = 0 \quad\) implying \(f(t) = e^t \quad\)for this range of \(t-\)values.

Finally if \(t > 2\) then \(t − 1 > 0\) and \(t − 2 > 0\) and so

\(\quad u(t − 1) = 1, \quad u(t − 2) = 1 \quad \) giving \( \quad f(t) = e^t (1 − 1) = 0.\)
